Sure, I'd be happy to help you with that! Here's a possible implementation of the `classifyItem` method in Scala:
```
import scala.collection.mutable.Map
object ItemClassifier {
 def main(args: Array[String]): Unit = {
 val item = "banana"
 val itemType = classifyItem(item)
 println(s"The item $item is classified as $itemType.")
 }
 def classifyItem(item: String): String = {
 val animalKeywords = Set("meat", "poultry", "fish", "egg", "milk", "cheese")
 val vegetableKeywords = Set("fruit", "vegetable", "grain", "nut", "seed", "legume")
 val keywordCounts = Map("animal" -> 0, "vegetable" -> 0)
 // Check if the item contains any of the animal or vegetable keywords
 for (keyword <- animalKeywords) {
 if (item.toLowerCase.contains(keyword)) {
 keywordCounts("animal") += 1
 }
 }
 for (keyword <- vegetableKeywords) {
 if (item.toLowerCase.contains(keyword)) {
 keywordCounts("vegetable") += 1
 }
 }
 // Classify the item based on the keyword counts
 if (keywordCounts("animal") > keywordCounts("vegetable")) {
 "animal"
 } else if (keywordCounts("vegetable") > keywordCounts("animal")) {
 "vegetable"
 } else {
 "unclear"
 }
 }
}
```
This implementation uses two sets of keywords to identify whether an item is more likely to be an animal or a vegetable. The `animalKeywords` set includes words commonly associated with animal-based foods, such as "meat", "poultry", and "fish", while the `vegetableKeywords` set includes words commonly associated with plant-based foods, such as "fruit", "vegetable", and "grain". 
The method then counts how many animal and vegetable keywords are present in the input item, and classifies the item based on which type of keyword is more prevalent. If there are an equal number of animal and vegetable keywords, the method returns "unclear".
You can modify the sets of keywords to suit your needs, or use a different approach altogether. I hope this helps!

